ions for children's services. The author: provides a clear conceptual understanding of five perspectives on well-being: need, rights, poverty, quality of life and social exclusion demonstrates the value of each perspective charts levels of child well-being in an inner-London community, including violated rights and social exclusion sets out the features that children's services must have if they are to improve child well-being defined in these terms This book should be read by everyone involved in developing, implementing and evaluating children's services, including researchers, policy makers and practitioners.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aChild welfarezGreat Britain. 0aChildrenxServices forxEvaluationzGreat Britain. 0aChildrenxSocial conditionszGreat Britain. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Children's Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBristol University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-1995z97831111962130 cprintz978184742065740uhttps://doi.org/10.56687/9781847423399?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781847423399423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781847423399/original  a978-3-11-119621-3  Bristol University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-1995c1995d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles